Sure, here is an example of how to create a popup message using JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Popup Message</title>
</head>
<body>

    <button onclick="showPopup()">Show Popup</button>

    <script>
        function showPopup() {
            var popup = document.createElement('div');
            popup.className = 'popup';
            popup.innerHTML = '<p>This is a message from the popup window.</p>';

            document.body.appendChild(popup);

            setTimeout(function() {
                popup.remove();
            }, 3000);
        }
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, when the user clicks the "Show Popup" button, a new div element with the class "popup" is created and appended to the body of the HTML document. The innerHTML of the div is set to the message that will be displayed in the popup. After 3 seconds, the popup is removed from the document using the remove() method.

